@flexiarg plos-npt-with-small-n/training-role-feature-register
@title Present Training Findings as Role Features With Extract Support
@keywords training, education, course-leader, thematic-analysis, role-features, rehabilitation
@audience education researchers, training evaluators, qualitative authors
@tone technical
@style pattern
@source-dois [10.1371/journal.pone.0312943 10.1186/s12913-021-06977-1 10.1186/s12913-019-4398-1]
@references [plos-npt-with-small-n/quote-table-not-quote-flood plos-npt-with-small-n/barrier-enabler-strategy-display]

! conclusion: Training and education qualitative papers should present findings as role features, competencies, or implementation conditions rather than as loose positive attributes.  Named themes such as manager, communicator, mediator, guide, and experienced professional work because they describe what the role must do, then support each feature with extracts and practical implications.

  + context: The PLOS rehabilitation higher-education exemplar structures Results around five course-leader features and pairs each with illustrative extract tables.  The BMC train-the-trainer cousins are useful for positioning because they similarly attend to training cascades, facilitation, organisational support, and practice impact, though their venue register is not PLOS ONE.

  + IF:
    The pattern operates on the axis: admired trait <-> functional role feature.
    Irreducible: a training finding becomes useful when it tells the reader what role-work is required, not merely which qualities participants liked.

  + HOWEVER:
    Real costs: role-feature naming can sound normative and may over-unify diverse participant accounts.  Keep feature labels close to the data and use extracts to show range, not just endorsement.
    Active dynamic: education papers often drift into generic virtues: flexible, empathic, experienced, collaborative.  The register strengthens when each virtue is tied to a work situation.

    + FAILURE-MODES:
      - Trait-list: themes are adjectives without role-work or implementation consequence.
      - Extract-as-endorsement: quotes show participants liked the trainer but not what the trainer did.
      - Training-effect-overreach: qualitative perceptions are presented as evidence that training improved outcomes.
      - Cousin-venue-contamination: BMC train-the-trainer structures are copied wholesale into a PLOS register rather than used for literature positioning.

  + THEN: Turn traits into functional features.
    + COMPOSITIONS:
      (1) Role-feature heading.
          Heading schema: "Theme N: A <functional role noun>"
          Effect: makes the feature readable as work, not personality.
      (2) Feature-extract table.
          Columns: feature, situation, participant extract, role-work demonstrated.
          Effect: shows how the feature operates.
      (3) Practice implication bridge.
          Schema: {:feature <x> :training-design-implication <y> :scope <similar education/training contexts>}
          Effect: turns qualitative themes into design implications without claiming measured effectiveness.

    + CHECK:
      Engaged when every training theme names a role-work demand and is supported by extracts showing that work.  Failing when the Results section reads as a list of desirable personal qualities.
